-- India’s Rupee Declines Most in a Week Before Fed, RBI Meetings
-- B y   J e a n e t t e   R o d r i g u e s
-- 2013-06-17T04:53:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-06-17/india-s-rupee-declines-most-in-a-week-before-fed-rbi-meetings.html
India’s rupee dropped the most in a
week on concern the Federal Reserve will signal a reduction in
asset purchases that have boosted inflows to  emerging markets .  Fed Chairman Ben S. Bernanke and the policy-setting Federal
Open Market Committee start a two-day meeting tomorrow. The U.S.
central bank is buying $85 billion of debt a month to spur the
world’s largest economy, and has kept interest rates near zero
since December 2008. The Reserve Bank of India will hold its
 repurchase  rate at 7.25 percent at a review today, according to
15 of 25 economists in a Bloomberg survey. Ten see a 25 basis
point cut. The rupee fell in each of the last six weeks and
touched a record low of 58.9850 per dollar on June 11.  “The rupee’s vulnerability has been particularly high due
to its external funding requirements, although it may show some
tentative signs of recovery over coming days as its sell-off has
looked overdone,”  Mitul Kotecha , global head of foreign-exchange strategy at Credit Agricole CIB in Hong Kong, wrote in
a research report today. “Given the recent signs of improvement
on the inflation front, a rate cut is unlikely.”  The rupee slid 0.5 percent to 57.8200 per dollar as of 10
a.m. in Mumbai, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. That’s
the biggest drop since June 10. The greenback’s 14-day relative
strength index versus the rupee was at 68, near the 70 threshold
that indicates the Indian currency may have fallen too much.  One-month implied volatility, a gauge of expected moves in
the exchange rate used to price options, rose nine basis points,
or 0.09 percentage point, to 10.99 percent.  Wholesale Prices  Wholesale prices  rose  4.7 percent in May from a year
earlier, the least since October 2009, official data showed June
14.  India ’s current-account deficit increased to a record high
of around 5 percent of gross domestic product in the year
through March 31, the government estimates.  Three-month onshore rupee forwards fell 0.5 percent from
June 14 to 58.72 per dollar, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. Offshore non-deliverable contracts dropped 0.2
percent to 58.74. Forwards are agreements to buy or sell assets
at a set price and date. Non-deliverable contracts are settled
in dollars.  To contact the reporter on this story:
